<h1>From Francis Fauquier</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sr</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Willmsburgh Sepr 16[29]th 1758</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I am obliged to you for the particular Acct you have sent me of the State of our Affairs wch I received by Jenkins on the 9th with Mr Gists Letter (by wch it appears he is not very sollicitous to make such a Return) and a Copy of your Correspondence wth Coll Bouquet: all wch tend to corroberate the Opinion we had before entertaind of your Zeal for the Service of this Colony. I have not returnd Coll Bouquets Letter, as the Assembly wch are now convened may perhaps call for it: but it shall be returned to you whenever you desire it.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>Since it is determined to go by Loyal hanning, I hope the Difficulties attending that Road are not so great as apprehended; that the army may reach Fort du Quesne this year; otherwise I much fear whether the ardor this Colony has shewn to support the war will continue for another Year, the Flame being a little stifled by the inactivity of this Campaign. But one glorious stroke will reanimate us. My Interest here can yet be of no Consideration, yet I will use my Endeavours wth the Assembly that our Troops may not be weakend for another year but I much doubt of my Success.</p>
<p>The Treasury is exhausted and I cannot yet say what the assembly will do to replenish it. Arrears must undoubtedly be paid, and you may be assured the first Money that comes there shall be applyed to the Payment of the Army, that they may not have any Room for Discontent from that Quarter.</p>
<p>I have directed the Letters I have received from you and Coll Byrd to be laid before the assembly as you will see by my Speech wch I send you herewith,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> and must wait their pleasure in Relation to the Major of Brigade as I have it not in my power to issue such a Commission the Number of Officers being limited by the last act of assembly by wch the second Regiment was raised. I shall always recommend it to them, to let you have every thing that is necessary for the Service.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>I have detained Jenkins till the House of Burgesses had taken the affair of the Regiments into Consideration and voted their Subsistance, for all the Money before granted was exhausted. I hope your Men are not uneasy but it was impossible for me to provide for their pay before. Mr Boyd may have 5000 whenever
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-06-02-pb-0023">[23]</span>
he pleases to come or send for it as I have wrote to him this Day.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0004-ptr">4</a></p>
<p>We are impatient to have frequent News from your Quarter in the present situation of Affairs. I am Sr wth great Esteem yr Very Hum. Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Fran. Fauquier</p>
<div class="dateline-closer">Sepr 29th<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0005" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0005-ptr">5</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0023-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>In his letter to Fauquier, 2 Sept. 1758, GW enclosed copies of letters that he had written to Bouquet. On 19 Sept. Fauquier sent to the House of Burgesses <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">several Letters</span> that he had received from GW, General Forbes, Col. William Byrd, and Lt. Col. George Mercer (<span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;"><span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ H. R. McIlwaine and John Pendleton Kennedy, eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the House of Burgesses of Virginia&lt;/i&gt;. 13 vols. Richmond, 190515. ]">JHB</span>, 17581761</span>, 1112), but none from Bouquet is mentioned. From the time he became colonel of the reconstituted Virginia Regiment in the fall of 1755, GW and the acting governor, first Robert Dinwiddie and now Fauquier, had used William Jenkins to carry letters back and forth between Williamsburg and Winchester or Fort Cumberland.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>A printed copy of Fauquiers speech to the Virginia assembly, 14 Sept., was enclosed (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>). It was delivered on 15 Sept. (<span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;"><span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ H. R. McIlwaine and John Pendleton Kennedy, eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the House of Burgesses of Virginia&lt;/i&gt;. 13 vols. Richmond, 190515. ]">JHB</span>, 17581761</span>, 45).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>For references to the appointment of a brigade major for the Virginia forces, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0255&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0255-fn-0002#GEWN-02-05-02-0255-fn-0002" class="document">GW to Francis Halkett, 21 July 1758, n.2</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>On 26 Sept. the House of Burgesses resolved to raise 20,000 to support the two Virginia regiments. The House passed the bill on 1 Oct., and Fauquier signed it on 12 October. For a discussion of the terms of An Act for the defence of the Frontiers of this Colony (7 <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William Waller Hening, ed. &lt;i&gt;The Statutes at Large; Being a Collection of All the Laws of Virginia, from the First Session of the Legislature, in the Year 1619&lt;/i&gt;. 13 vols. 181923. Reprint. Charlottesville, Va., 1969. ]">Hening</span> 17179), see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0066&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-06-02-0066-fn-0002#GEWN-02-06-02-0066-fn-0002" class="document">William Ramsay to GW, 17 Oct. 1758, n.2</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0023-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>Fauquier evidently added the last two paragraphs of the letter on 29 September.</p>

</div>
</div>
